I was surprised we could get seats at the bar and it wasn't more packed at happy hour time than it was.< /text>< Pics>

< user>
117547720381251494227</user>
< Text>
This is one of the few bars in LA where I can actually stay until closing! They have a beautiful view of the city which is going to hard to come by with all the construction happening off sunset.There is a entrance on Sunset, that only sometimes has a doorman, don't know why...b but you can easily enter through the Mondrian entrance. Just head straight back and it will be on your right. there are plenty of couches outside and a smaller covered seating area generally reserved for parties/bottle service, by the bar. The waiters and hostesses are friendly. Restrooms are "downstairs" to your left, or straight ahead when you first enter through the roped off entrance. Drinks are a bit pricey, but they are heavy pours..how I have not seen someone drunk fall into the pool or tumble down the stairs I don't know. A good place to people watch, have a sexy drink date, or mingle with friends.</Text>

<Date>1594179967877</Date><rate>4</rate>< review>
I've gone here for big events such as the Corona Electric Beach events as well as the Wicked Paradise events here, seeing some of the coolest DJs such as Illenium, Prince Fox, Cheat Codes, and Tim Gunter. It's also really easy to get up close to the DJs at the dance floor. I usually go to Skybar to dance for these kind of events rather than swim so I can't speak for the swimming pool. However, there are a lot of cute floaties here. They had a great bucket of Corona special one time I came here, as well as a margarita deal another time.</review>

1502555590593< /date>
<Rating>4</Rating>< Review>
Quite on an early Friday night. 21+ to smoke hookah w/ real tobacco. 18+ for alternative, but you can't sit with anyone smoking tobacco. Maximum of 3 per hookah, so parties of 4 must order 2, unless you get a premium hookah. Non smoker pay a $5(?) Sitting fee. I've never been to a hookah lounge with so many rules. Not sure if this is standard at other lounges, but it was new for me.</Review>

< text>
The drink was really good but I was a little bit disappointed in the popcorn chicken. The drink I got was really tasty but it had a lot of ice in it. I got the Mango/Passionfruit flavor black tea with lychee jelly and I must say it was a really good choice combo on my part! The only complaint I have is with the ice because not a lot of people like a lot of ice in their drinks. As for the popcorn chicken, it looked so good and ready to eat with the sauce I ordered to go along with it. After a several bites into the popcorn chicken, it just didn‚Äôt taste good anymore. It was slightly over cooked even with the right amount of seasoning and sauce. I highly recommend just a couple of test runs after closing to perfect the popcorn chicken. That‚Äôs about all I have to say in my review! A huge thanks to UberEats for delivery.< /text>

< Text>
The car I was given, a Toyota Corolla, was very nice, clean,  and handled very well. It was ready when we went to pick it up and check-out was very easy. The car got excellent gas mileage. I would say we averaged about 35 miles a gallon .
The only reason I'm giving four stars instead of five is that when they gave us two keys, they were fastened together on a band that was crimped in metal , so they could not be separated. When I return the car, I brought this up to the young lady who checked me in , who basically and insistently  blew me off about the keys, and  told me I could have used a "bolt cutter"  (which I normally don't have with me on vacation). I also figured since the keys and the key holder were the property of Enterprise, I should not damage them. Enterprise could easily put the keys on a screw together key loop.<//Text>

< review>
If you want great reliable customer service without a long wait I would go somewhere else!

I'm not completely unsatisfied but not satisfied with my rental experience at this location. The first time I rented here I had some issues that  were completely taken care of with great customer service! This last time I rented for me is not the same out come. I showed up 15 minutes early only to see the manager drive off in my rental car to take her daughter to school. The gal at the front counter, who was nice and well dressed, rushed through my paper work and told me they had no other cars and I had to wait. When the manager came back with my car the gal had to wait to get the keys from her and then I was told the car was empty and I either had to go get gas or wait while they got gas. At this time I point out that this is unacceptable not only because I've been waiting but that this is now my time that I'm paying for the car and it should be ready. The manager lied to me and tells me the car just came in this morning and they hadn't had time to get fuel. When I pointed out that I saw her taking her daughter to school in it and that she should have gotten fuel on the way back she got a rude sassy attitude. She stated that I should be happy because I got an upgrade to a" higher end car" already. Then She tried to give me multiple lower grade cars than what I rented after I was told that was the only car available. Finely she gave me an up grade to a suv that had fuel and gave me half the fuel tank for free only after I pointed out fuel economy is different from the type of car I rented which is why I'm renting. Another associate, who was new, was sent out with me when I found out that the insurance I asked for had not been applied when I first got the paper work. He apologized profusely as he got me out as fast as he could because I had been there for 45 minutes already and the only customer there.

On my return I had to wait, along with other customers, for 10 minutes in an empty office before we asked next door when we would be helped. The manager who was so rude in the beginning helped me check out. At this time I found out that I got every insurance there was which was not what I asked for. The manager was extremely nice this time and fixed the mistake of the insurance. Then as I was leaving she said I would get a survey and made it very clear that I needed to be "completely satisfied" because that's her only "passing grade". Which made it clear to me why she asked the entire time of checking out if I was "completely satisfied" with my rental experience.

The vehicle I was upgraded to was very nice. I wouldn't mind renting it again. Unfortunately it doesn't make up for the lack of organization and sassy attitude of the manager.<//review>

< Text>
First of all. Good looking place if you are looking to stay there more than an hour with fam and friends. Parking is a problem sometimes. Not necessarily the restaurant problem. Pupusas are just right give it a 10/10. Salsa (spicy) 10/10 Curtido (spicy) 9/10 Horchata de morro 6/10. Thats the good things I can talk about this place. Now on the second hand... It is pricy. You can only use your debid card if you are spending more than $15 that you will if you are looking for a hole meal for yourself. The worst thing is having to wait for your food. I would like to recomend the owner of the place to hire more employees because that is an issue.< /Text>

<Name>Colin Hare<//Name><Date>1596499334213</Date>< rating>
1<//rating>
< Text>
Short answer - if I could give them zero or negative stars I would... Long answer - see below...

Over 5 years ago a few family members and myself purchased a combined total of about 6 AR lowers and some other AR parts from solar tactical, the staff was helpful and accommodating. I recently have been in the market to buy a handful of new firearms and have some work done to my existing firearms, I wanted to go through Solar Tactical because I had such a positive experience the first time.

The 2nd and 3rd experiences were so terrible compared to that first time, I have tried to give Solar Tactical a chance to rectify these bad experiences - but unfortunately they seem to not care about giving me a good customer service experience. I own my own company and I know that more often than not a bad customer service experience can be turned into a positive experience if the necessary respect, customer care, and time are given... Solar Tactical was disrespectful throughout this whole experience over the past 2 months.

I went through the process to purchase a new handgun in July of 2020, the first thing that I find unacceptable was that they are not answering their phone and are not letting the customers know this... the only way I could get a hold of them was through Instagram messages, and even this form of communication was not consistent. I made an unnecessary trip from the east bay to Livermore because they were not answering their phone or communicating... this was because I purchased the firearm and waited the 10 day waiting period then called and messaged to make an appointment to come pick up the firearm... no one got back to me and when I got to the store I found out that the 10 day waiting period is more like a 15 or 20 day waiting period because of Covid... but no one told me this, so I wasted an afternoon.in traffic.

When I finally did get a call to come pick up this firearm it was supplied with a trigger lock and the employee told me to follow the law I should put the trigger lock on the gun for transportation... the firearm frame was aluminum with Cerakote paint... the supplied trigger lock ended up scratching the finish on my brand new gun before I was even able to get it home, and when I called about this rather than having someone offer help or a solution I was told how it was my fault...

The final issue I had was from some work I had done on one of my existing firearms. I had a Cerakote paint  job done to the slide of my glock 34... I had some minor pitting on my 8 year old glock 34 so I brought my wife with me and had her help me choose a new color for my gun. The staff was helpful in including her in the process and bringing her behind the counter to look at the paint jobs they had on their EDC pistols as well as reviewing options on the computer they had behind the counter. My wife chose a very specific color and even pointed it out on a paint chip, it was a very dark purple like grape or grimace. Not only was I told it would be 2 weeks and ended up being almost 2 months... which is fine, but I would have liked to have been notified, but the gun came back LAVENDER and again I was told how this was my fault because the colors can look different than what is on the computer... then why would you show me a paint chip... since this work has been done no one would answer my call or respond to messages.

Unacceptable guys, so as you choose a gun store to support in these trying times and climate of gun ownership in California... CHOOSE ANYONE BUT SOLOAR TACTICAL, I would even be happy to help you find an alternative gun store.< /Text>

< review>
Worst customer service ever. It really deserves 0 stars.  When I walked in there were 4 or 5 good ol' boy's talking behind the counter so I assumed they all worked there. There was a man and a woman together and one of the good ol' boy's was helping them with an AR. They were the only other customers in the store beside me.  One of the good ol' boys some bearded douche bag walks over to me and asked me if he could help me. I wanted a hard to find caliber of ammo so I asked if they had any.
Douche bag checks his computer which was right in front of me and starts muttering under his breath. He then turns to the good ol' boy who was helping the man an woman with the AR. He starts talking to them and just left me hanging, then he storms off to the back of the store with the couples AR. He didn't even tell me if they had the ammo I wanted. So I left.
Those guys are all Douche bags and I will never ever go back to the good ol boy's place again. I wouldn't recommend them if they were the last gun shop on earth.
I've been around guns and gun stores for over 30 years and this was the worst customer service EVER! I wouldn't spend a penny in that Piece of S**t  store and to all who read this don't waste your time going there. If you want a good gun shop go to Tracy Rifle and Pistol or Elite Arms in Manteca. They are great and know how to treat customers.< /review>

<Pics>None< /Pics><Text>Love this local place that offers good Thai food. You're able to pick your spice level (1 - 10, with 10 being the spiciest), which is a great option to stay neutral or sweat it out. Just be careful not to get an already spicy dish marked with a pepper & think you're okay getting the same level of spice you did last time without the pepper marking... You may not enjoy the dish as much. The staff is super friendly but they may not always see you if you're in one of the corner tables and you're in a rush to leave...you may need to flag them down. Food is quick, delicious, and filling. You won't be disappointed!

Tip: better to be mild and then be able to increase the heat level if you need more .</Text><user_id>101023979759551678024<//user_id><Rate>4</Rate>< time>

<gmapID>0x808f7e3d23f5dddd:0x3342559449ab0793< /gmapID><Review>Wow, just wow! Where do I even start? Dandelion is simply awesome and a must-visit.

I was so tempted by all their creations, so naturally I had to do the Chef's chocolate tasting flight. At $14, it's not cheap for the small portion sizes that you get, but I thought I got good value out of it

Items in the tasting:
- A spritzer made using chocolate from Belize (wasn't heavily chocolately, more like a light chocolate palate cleanser)
- Profiteroles using chocolate from Liberia (it was really good)
- S'more using chocolate from Ecuador (Absolutely divine! My fav!)
- Passionfruit chocolate macaron using chocolate from Madagascar (this was ok)
- Panna Cotta with chocolate from Venezuela (so good! My second fav!)

Now that I have had the tasting, my next visit will be focusing on getting the items that I like, as the regular items are bigger in size. Overall, I think this is as good as it gets for a small local chocolate factory/cafe!! A++

Check out @instantonium on Instagram for more great eats</Review><rate>5< /rate>< Resp>

<review>This review is an interview:
What did you like about it?
The best marshmallows I've ever had in my life. I felt good about the ethics. Supporting small global cocoa growers. Good place to have some fun and learn about chocolate. Free tasting helps it feel like a community experience, and the mission hot chocolate was excellent. Spice+cocoa was just perfect.

What can't you miss at this place?
The truffles are the best gift I've ever gotten. Don't miss on the chance to share something unique

What should people know?
They have nice seating, restrooms, and interesting info on how the chocolate is made. They also have delicious pastries for those who aren't in a chocolate mood.</review>< Pictures>

<GmapID>0x808f7e3d23f5dddd:0x3342559449ab0793</GmapID><userid>105987593835493922624<//userid><Review>I tried Dandelion Chocolate on the recommendation of a friend who I was meeting in Mission. It is located on the stretch of Valencia which is home to a lot of decent restaurants. Parking in this area is always tough but you can find something on the side streets and walk a little.

The one word to describe Dandelion Chocolate would be hipster. As much as I would like to avoid that word this place screams for hipsters by hipsters. It has shelves with trendy chocolate bars (~$8/each) on the right and left-hand side and a large open area where they make the drinks and conduct classes. I think I was there around noon and the place was pretty packed so it is definitely popular. I knew what I wanted to try so I walked over to the counter and ordered a Frozen hot chocolate ($5.75). After ordering it was a short 10-minute wait and I had my drink.

I sat on one of the large open tables only to find that it was dirty and needed to be properly wiped down. Anyway, the frozen hot chocolate seems to be your typical ice blended drink (think Frappuccino) but with a lot more ice and rich chocolate. It is presented very well on a wooden plate and some whipped cream on top and a small cookie to go with it. It wasn‚Äôt something that blew my socks off but it was pretty good.

Price was also not too bad considering the location and the trendy setup. I later found out that they have opened a small outlet in the ferry building at the Embarcadero which is a-lot is closer to where I live so I guess I will be able to try to try some more stuff off their menu in due course as I liked what I got here.<//Review>< username>

<Review>This review is an interview:
What did you like about it?
The best marshmallows I've ever had in my life. I felt good about the ethics. Supporting small global cocoa growers. Good place to have some fun and learn about chocolate. Free tasting helps it feel like a community experience, and the mission hot chocolate was excellent. Spice+cocoa was just perfect.

What can't you miss at this place?
The truffles are the best gift I've ever gotten. Don't miss on the chance to share something unique

What should people know?
They have nice seating, restrooms, and interesting info on how the chocolate is made. They also have delicious pastries for those who aren't in a chocolate mood.< /Review><pictures>None<//pictures><response>None< /response><gmapID>0x808f7e3d23f5dddd:0x3342559449ab0793</gmapID></record></dataset><record>

<name>Malvika Agarwal</name>< Text>
Great chocolate.
Passive aggressive staff - we hung out at the restaurant expecting that the staff will tell us when when they are closing and then we will leave. Then abruptly the hostess tells us that our "grace period" is up and we should leave. I didn't even know we were on "grace period". So If you are there late at night make sure to do the hostesses job for her and keep tabs on the closing time and leave promptly before they close if you don't want the chocolate in your mouth to turn sour. I am so tired of San Francisco restaurants feeling like they are doing you a favor.< /Text>

<userid>105987593835493922624<//userid><user_name>Ahmad Jetha</user_name><time>1530385410086</time><rating>4<//rating><Review>I tried Dandelion Chocolate on the recommendation of a friend who I was meeting in Mission. It is located on the stretch of Valencia which is home to a lot of decent restaurants. Parking in this area is always tough but you can find something on the side streets and walk a little.

The one word to describe Dandelion Chocolate would be hipster. As much as I would like to avoid that word this place screams for hipsters by hipsters. It has shelves with trendy chocolate bars (~$8/each) on the right and left-hand side and a large open area where they make the drinks and conduct classes. I think I was there around noon and the place was pretty packed so it is definitely popular. I knew what I wanted to try so I walked over to the counter and ordered a Frozen hot chocolate ($5.75). After ordering it was a short 10-minute wait and I had my drink.

I sat on one of the large open tables only to find that it was dirty and needed to be properly wiped down. Anyway, the frozen hot chocolate seems to be your typical ice blended drink (think Frappuccino) but with a lot more ice and rich chocolate. It is presented very well on a wooden plate and some whipped cream on top and a small cookie to go with it. It wasn‚Äôt something that blew my socks off but it was pretty good.

Price was also not too bad considering the location and the trendy setup. I later found out that they have opened a small outlet in the ferry building at the Embarcadero which is a-lot is closer to where I live so I guess I will be able to try to try some more stuff off their menu in due course as I liked what I got here.< /Review>< pictures>
[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMBOJ01-3ARmH9BIarzvqnvdk7ckzsR2NRau7lY=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP8D5IWu3w-GW06gecG2JQYMCtuPTD9LdvSzHxm=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pictures>

< review>
The smell emanating onto Valencia Street led us into the sensory ‚Äúexperience‚Äù that is Dandelion Chocolate ‚Äì and while we‚Äôre not that big on sweets, we couldn‚Äôt really resist following our noses into this popular spot.. No one can.

After testing out a few chocolate samples from around the world and the bite-size home-made marshmallows, we grabbed a seat at the coffee bar for the feature attraction. For most, that‚Äôs usually the hot chocolate.

For us, it was the beautiful marriage of dark chocolate and coffee, otherwise knows as their speciality Marocchino drink, that got our full attention. Equal portion dark chocolate and espresso, this drink is served with a side of fluffy whipped cream to add that sweetness right when you need it.< /review>

< text>
A must-visit for all Chocolate lovers! Upon entry to your left, they have a nice variety of chocolate bars (nicely wrapped) with trays of samples you can taste. The bars are perfect for gift giving & they come from exotic countries such as Belize, Guatamala, Madagascar, Peru, etc. They offer factory tours, tasting, classes, recipes, & an on-site drink/dessert menu. There's something for everyone here.</text>

< Review>
The air was thick with chocolate as we entered what feels like an old warehouse gone hipster.

We sampled some bits of dark chocolate from Ecuador, Tanzania, wherever, ranging from 70% to the pure real deal of 100% cacao. Yowsa!

Ordering a couple of overpriced glasses of "traditional" hot chocolate, with almond milk instead of the regular cow variety, we sat at a communal wooden table, sipping our viscous elixirs that took us to another world as we discussed the possibility of minimum chocolate standards for the masses akin to minimum wages.

Yes, we were high on life, in albeit away from the rest of the world.<//Review>

< Text>
I am not even a chocolate fan and I like Dandelion Chocolate... a lot. The place smells amazing for one, and their chocolate bars are so good! I love that you can sample them before deciding which bar to devour on your own. They have a large selection of chocolate desserts and drinks and so forth, and I was really tempted to get the chocolate dessert sampler... But it was just before dinner so I didn't want to ruin my appetite.

Dandelion bars make great gifts for whoever loves and appreciates good chocolate - I love that they have year and place of origin, and it makes every batch super special and difficult to find elsewhere. A super cool gift I saw in store too was a make your own chocolate kit - with beans and everything!

I found out when I visited that they have chocolate factory tours - if I ever go back, I'm hitting that for sure.<//Text>

<userid>105852221659310339934< /userid><Name>Charles Thayer</Name><Date>1475561970550<//Date><rating>5< /rating>< text>
Great chocolate store, which is definitely foodie-worthy, and functions as an exhibit of the whole chocolate making and curing process.  They have delicious tidbits and little bites, along with fantastic hot chocolate and mocha coffees.  The die-hard chocolate lover will want the European drinking chocolate, the Mission resident will want the spicy Mission Hot Chocolate, and the kids will love the hot chocolate or "PB&J".

The also sell bars, beans, and a few other gift items.  My least favorite drink has been the mocha cappuccino because it's relative light on chocolate.</text>

<Review>Cute and busy little chocolate cafe right on Valencia. With the outdoor seating, it's popular during warmer days. My husband and I got a seat inside on a crowded Saturday; I got the spicy mocha with cayenne pepper. It was similar to a Mexican Hot Chocolate, rich and chocolatey with an espresso kick. If you're getting a hot chocolate, don't hesitate to top it with the house-made marshmallows, and the chocolate covered shortbread they sell is heavenly. Snag a seat at the bar to watch the chocolate-makers do their work, as a sign says they love questions.< /Review>< pics>

< Text>
Cute and busy little chocolate cafe right on Valencia. With the outdoor seating, it's popular during warmer days. My husband and I got a seat inside on a crowded Saturday; I got the spicy mocha with cayenne pepper. It was similar to a Mexican Hot Chocolate, rich and chocolatey with an espresso kick. If you're getting a hot chocolate, don't hesitate to top it with the house-made marshmallows, and the chocolate covered shortbread they sell is heavenly. Snag a seat at the bar to watch the chocolate-makers do their work, as a sign says they love questions.</Text>

< review>
Wow. This was an amazing find!
I tried their hot chocolate and it was amazing. The balance between sugar and chocolate and the texture of the chocolate was superb.
NOTE: If you like "sweet" chocolate, you might be disappointed by their offerings.
These guys have an awesome chocolate--it is all about the texture. Do not avoid their chocolate just because it is not loaded with sugar.
Try everything they have. I loved almost everything I tried; I love dark chocolate and low-sugar chocolate.
Highly recommended.</review>

<Text>This place is magical. From the moment you open the door and the sweet smell of chocolate gives you a big hug you can tell you've come to a good place. While I've bought Dandelion Chocolate bars for a while now because I'm obsessed with their gorgeous packaging, I only recently realized that they are made with just 2 ingredients: cocoa beans and cane sugar. That's incredible! And the people that work here are more than happy to tell you just how they do it. Their cafe has delicious pastries and drinks, of which I highly recommend trying the Lemon Ginger Iced Chocolate - my new favorite treat!</Text><Rate>5< /Rate>< UserId.>

< UserId.>
108158025167612496070< /UserId.>
<user_name>Julie Leong</user_name><date>1524772895229< /date>< Rating>
5< /Rating>
<text>One of my favorite places in SF! Located on hip, bustling Valencia St, Dandelion Chocolate is a chocolate-lover's heaven. Handmade, single-origin chocolates and desserts. Must-tries: frozen hot chocolate (for hot/sunny days) and the European drinking chocolate (super thick, hot, rich -- sip slowly). There are complimentary housemade marshmallows at the drink station as well. The only negative is how crowded this place gets now.

Dandelion also does fantastic, $5/person tours and demonstrations of the small facilities that include tastings of chocolate pieces and chocolate straight from the melting vat. These tours are booked up MONTHS in advance though, so plan ahead!<//text><Pics>None</Pics>< Response>
None</Response>

116765328706403133339</UserId.>
<user_name>Connie Florez<//user_name><time>1527061064184<//time><rate>5<//rate>< Text>
What a find! I'm so happy to have stumbled across Dandelion Chocolate. From the moment you walk in, you know you're in for a treat. All that chocolately goodness is in the air and it smells heavenly. The chocolate samples while waiting in line was a productive use of time. You can learn first hand how the varied the flavors can be. The staff are super friendly. There's a nice selection of baked goods to sample from. I was pleasantly surprised that my baked good weren't over-the-top sweet. The European hot chocolate and iced chocolate chai were amazing. You can sit and enjoy your chocolate treats while watching the chocolate makers in action. I love that Dandelion is all about educating people on the whole chocolate making process. Next on my list is having a  factory tour.<//Text>

<review>Perfect sweet stop on a cold afternoon in SF! I've heard so many things about dandelion chocolate and their hot chocolate, I had to go in the store haha. Though I was only there for about 10 minutes, I could tell that they put a lot of effort in their chocolates. < rating>
5< /rating>
<username>Julie Leong< /username>< review>
One of my favorite places in SF! Located on hip, bustling Valencia St, Dandelion Chocolate is a chocolate-lover's heaven. Handmade, single-origin chocolates and desserts. Must-tries: frozen hot chocolate (for hot/sunny days) and the European drinking chocolate (super thick, hot, rich -- sip slowly). There are complimentary housemade marshmallows at the drink station as well. The only negative is how crowded this place gets now.

Dandelion also does fantastic, $5/person tours and demonstrations of the small facilities that include tastings of chocolate pieces and chocolate straight from the melting vat. These tours are booked up MONTHS in advance though, so plan ahead!</review>

There was little else to purchase beyond single-origin chocolate bars, but plenty of opportunity to sample these and make sure you are getting something you will enjoy. <Text>Enjoyable and educational. Did you know, Dandelion is the ONLY place in the Western United States that makes smoothies out of the pulpy stuff in the pod in which cacao ferments. In the relatively short time this location has been open, we are seeing the long-line-for-popular-mission-place phenomenon. < review>
It's basically a Mission cliche: a store with amazing food (or products) with bad hours and poor customer service. If you manage to make it there when it's open you'll be able to get extremely rich and delicious hot chocolate and other treats. The hipster behind the counter will probably look irritated to serve you, but hey maybe it's performance art or they are only working ironically.

I recommend the original hot chocolate over the mission. Both are good but the spices in the mission I thought were too strong. As for their chocolate bars: go for the Madagascar it tastes like it has sweet fruit in it.</review>

<Time>1462045288525<//Time><response>None</response>< Text>
As an adult, this place is what Ghirardelli was for me as a kid. It's part production facility, part store, and part kitchen. You can buy chocolate bars, eat well-made desserts, and sample single-origin chocolate from all over the world. The chocolate is on par with the more expensive chocolate I've had; if I remember correctly, it's over $8/bar.

Is it the best chocolate in the world? Frankly I don't know enough about chocolate. I've tried Ritual, which some people consider the best, and I think it's very good. Dandelion is also very good. That's about as specific as I can get.< /Text>

< Rate>

< Review>
Personally, I don't feel Dandelion Chocolate is worth the hype. I've been 3 times, each time I ate there and got different items (1st time: a chocolate chip cookie, 2nd time: the Chef's chocolate sampler, 3rd time: a chocolate brownie). The stuff tastes good, but its expensive and really hyped up for what it is. Every time I've gone there has been a line out the door, and sitting inside is a mess. If you sit at one of the front tables it's always crowded by people trying to get their orders. The crowds really take away from the experience for me. They do have cute gift boxes full of chocolate - just be sure to take it to-go!<//Review>

< Text>
So many reasons to love this place... Ranging from a 100% dark chocolate bar (that, when eaten properly (rest a small piece on your tongue, when you haven't had anything sweet recently), is delectable), to the Cacao Fruit Smoothie, which tastes nothing like chocolate (because it's not from the beans ‚Äì it's white!), it's just a dreamy icy fruity sweet drink, a great counterpoint to the 100%, if you go in that order. Or there's the PB&J bar, or the Dulce de Leche, or... Yeah, lots of yummy in between the extremes of the 100% and the smoothie.</Text>

< text>
So so overrated! Is it good yeah is it amazing no, not at all!

It was our first time here, so R & I shared the Chef's Tasting so we can have a little of everything. The cocoa spritzer was not good, at all! The other things were good, average. Like a peanut butter and jelly cup it's pretty hard not mess it up. The down side was that considering that it's a chocolate place there wasn't an emphasis enough on the actual chocolate. We were expecting way more chocolaty flavors from those deserts. My favorite by far was the nib-infused panna cotta.

I will come here again and try their drinks because they looked better than the deserts.<//text>

< Review>
Had the frozen mocha hot chocolate which was nice. The cacao fruit smoothies don't taste too much like chocolate but a refreshing drink.

Today for desserts they had pumpkin pie in a jar, malt cookie sandwiches, nutella stuffed cookies, a smores dessert, and a flight of brownies. They also sell 3 chocolate bars for $20 which makes a nice gift.

Service is good and my favorite place to sit is along the bar that leads toward the restroom; much quieter than from the seats up front.< /Review>

< Review>
I always drop in here to sample little pieces of chocolates for free when I pass by. Then one day, I actually decided to BUY something. Yeah, that was a fairly new concept for my Asian cheapskate brain. Yes, the double malt chocolate cook was $3.88 after tax but BOY WAS IT DELICIOUS. Chewy and not overly sweet. I had a taste of my friend's toffee chocolate brittle and that was very satisfying as well.

The bad? It's always busy, crowded, and bustling in there, which kind of ruins the vibe.</Review>

< Review>
Had the frozen mocha hot chocolate which was nice. The cacao fruit smoothies don't taste too much like chocolate but a refreshing drink.

Today for desserts they had pumpkin pie in a jar, malt cookie sandwiches, nutella stuffed cookies, a smores dessert, and a flight of brownies. They also sell 3 chocolate bars for $20 which makes a nice gift.

Service is good and my favorite place to sit is along the bar that leads toward the restroom; much quieter than from the seats up front.<//Review>

<user>116629445048031027717</user><username>Ryan Manzer<//username>< date>
1366518281808</date>
<rating>5</rating><text>If you are a true lover of chocolate in it's intense, mind altering deliciousness you should stop here.  One of the very few places in the entire country where you can see actual cocoa beans roasted and turned into bars of chocolate.  Give yourself over to a chocolate tasting experience that rivals the most sophisticated wine tasting you might have done in Napa or Sonoma county.  Since they only use the cocoa beans and sugar in the making of their chocolate, Dandelion chocolate bars express the climate and soil these beans inhabit, from Venezuela to Madagascar.  It doesn't hurt that the people here are quite friendly and informative.  Walking into this place one smell told me I was somewhere special.  To paraphrase one very nice person, Life is a journey, Dandelion chocolates is the destination.  You have arrived.< /text>< Pics>
None<//Pics>

<user_id>103890778932655872360< /user_id>< user_name>
Adrienne</user_name>
< Time>
1419624302228< /Time>
< rating>
5</rating>
< Review>
This is one of my favorite places in the city. I remember first walking into the shop and thinking, "Wow, whoever owns this shop must really love chocolate!"

Delicious chocolate with only two ingredients: cacao beans and sugar. They even offer free tours of their factory, where they tell you about how they source their beans, and the different machines they use in every part of the process from bean shelling to liquification.

The decor and interior design is also beautiful -- many of their serving tools I've learned are items they've curated while traveling around the world -- the tiny spoons from Japan, the oak serving platters from Italy.

It's a great (noisy, but I don't mind) place to read a book or get some work done.

I generally don't like dessert (it's too sweet) but the desserts here are to-die-for. They even have complimentary hand-made marshmallows that you can put in your coffee or hot chocolate.</Review>

<userid>108102745766268031532< /userid><user_name>Jonas Brandon</user_name><date>1490898661733< /date><rating>4</rating>< review>

< GmapID>
0x808f7e3d23f5dddd:0x3342559449ab0793<//GmapID>
</record></dataset><record>
< Rate>
4<//Rate>
<resp>None<//resp><user>103379264202553362035<//user>< text>
Due to my inability to find the Pie Fridays cart two weeks back, I had the good fortune of finally stumbling into this fantastic (not-so-)little chocolate shop that I'd completely forgotten I desperately wanted to try. My friend and I end up getting their:

* House Hot Chocolate - Ever since winter started settling in, I've been ordering hot chocolate almost every time I see it at a cafe. Dandelion's hot chocolate has probably been among the best I've had in recent memory, striking a great balance between sweet and bitter. Served on a little plate with a shortbread cookie and a few small pieces of their chocolate as well.

* Frozen Hot Chocolate - This one I was a little less fanatical about, only because it was on the darker, more bitter side of things. And I'm not even talking bittersweet, but more of a dark chocolate kind of bitter. That's not to say it wasn't enjoyable, but, unlike my chocolate, I definitely prefer my drinking chocolates a bit on the more sugary side. Like the other hot chocolate, this was also served with a cookie and chocolate.

* Dulce de Leche - From the shop's description, you already know this dessert bar is going to be on the sweet side. So, I was admittedly a little hesitant to order this along with the house hot chocolate. but they actually made for a great pairing, as the hot chocolate was bittersweet enough to offset the tasty decadence of this dessert.

* Smore - The smore was to the frozen hot chocolate as the dulce de leche was to the house hot chocolate: just okay. The flavors weren't bad, but the entire thing would have benefited greatly from being heated up to give the marshmallow that gooeyness one would expect from a campfire smore.

In addition to their cafe portion, they're also a regular chocolate shop with bars and other things for purchase (and sample!), and hold events and factory tours fairly frequently.

***Accessibility Info***

Venue - A huge space comprised of their chocolate factory, with limited regular seating towards the front, and bar counter seating along the "kitchen." The former is perfectly accessible, the latter, as expected, is not.

Bathroom - All the way towards the back, and also quite accessible.<//text>

< Review>
I saw this chocolate shop on the tv show Unique Sweets on the Cooking Channel last year, and since i was in the area dropped by. As soon as you walk in your smacked in the face with the smell of chocolate!! A great atmosphere with a great view of Valencia Street. I purchased the Nutella filled Chocolate Chip Cookies and the Dulce De Leche Bar. The Dulce De Leche bar is ridiculously good!! I definitely want to try the European Drinking Chocolate when I go back. I would recommend this place to anyone who loves chocolate.</Review>

< username>

<Gmap_id>0x808f7e3d23f5dddd:0x3342559449ab0793</Gmap_id>< Time>
1465162029671<//Time>
<user_id>103379264202553362035<//user_id><pictures>None</pictures>< text>
Due to my inability to find the Pie Fridays cart two weeks back, I had the good fortune of finally stumbling into this fantastic (not-so-)little chocolate shop that I'd completely forgotten I desperately wanted to try. My friend and I end up getting their:

* House Hot Chocolate - Ever since winter started settling in, I've been ordering hot chocolate almost every time I see it at a cafe. Dandelion's hot chocolate has probably been among the best I've had in recent memory, striking a great balance between sweet and bitter. Served on a little plate with a shortbread cookie and a few small pieces of their chocolate as well.

* Frozen Hot Chocolate - This one I was a little less fanatical about, only because it was on the darker, more bitter side of things. And I'm not even talking bittersweet, but more of a dark chocolate kind of bitter. That's not to say it wasn't enjoyable, but, unlike my chocolate, I definitely prefer my drinking chocolates a bit on the more sugary side. Like the other hot chocolate, this was also served with a cookie and chocolate.

* Dulce de Leche - From the shop's description, you already know this dessert bar is going to be on the sweet side. So, I was admittedly a little hesitant to order this along with the house hot chocolate. but they actually made for a great pairing, as the hot chocolate was bittersweet enough to offset the tasty decadence of this dessert.

* Smore - The smore was to the frozen hot chocolate as the dulce de leche was to the house hot chocolate: just okay. The flavors weren't bad, but the entire thing would have benefited greatly from being heated up to give the marshmallow that gooeyness one would expect from a campfire smore.

In addition to their cafe portion, they're also a regular chocolate shop with bars and other things for purchase (and sample!), and hold events and factory tours fairly frequently.

***Accessibility Info***

Venue - A huge space comprised of their chocolate factory, with limited regular seating towards the front, and bar counter seating along the "kitchen." The former is perfectly accessible, the latter, as expected, is not.

Bathroom - All the way towards the back, and also quite accessible.<//text>

<Resp>None<//Resp>< Text>
Still delicious after 2 years later but be warned they sell out of those amazing s'mores so come early or end up disappointed like we were =(

However, it did prompt me to try their super rich hot chocolate which I am happy to report is chocolate bliss. It's rich, indulgent, creamy nirvana

7x7 100 Best Things To Eat In SF Before You Die 2014

#20 Papua New Guinea S'more at Dandelion Chocolate

Simply put, the best smore I have had so far. The marshmallow had just the right amount of sweetness and texture. I loved that it was firm yet had such a soft cloudy mouth feel. It was paired with just the right balance of chocolate to graham cracker ratio. The touch of salt is what brought the entire dish together and would gladly go back for another.

I also decided to try the "Frozen" Hot Chocolate and Nutella Chocolate Chip Cookie. I can safely say I won't be back for those. The hot chocolate felt extremely watered down in both texture and flavor.

Overall Thoughts

I will be back for a S'more, you can count on that!<//Text>
